AB  - Human-machine interface (HMI) focuses on developing user interfaces (UI) where humans interact with digital systems. As the prevalence of robots in industrial settings increases, the complexity of human-robot interaction becomes increasingly critical. Designing intuitive and effective interfaces is essential to ensure robotic systems' safe and efficient operation. This paper explores the use of virtual reality (VR) as a human-centred interface for engineering teleoperation, focusing on the core functions of industrial robot teach pendants. We aim to develop a general VR-based robotic manipulator interface by analysing existing HMI and identifying potential VR enhancements. Our results suggest that VR-based interfaces have the potential to improve user experience (UX), efficiency, accuracy, and UI/UX design flexibility. This work intends to contribute to the VR teleoperation concept for other robotic systems like drones/unmanned aerial vehicles, autonomous underwater vehicles, and automated guided vehicles.
