AU  - Q. Dang
AU  - W. Shang
AU  - J. Fu
AU  - P. Lu
AU  - M. Guo
T2  - 2025 6th International Conference on Computer Engineering and Intelligent Control (ICCEIC)
AB  - As societal electricity demand continues to climb, the scale and complexity of power grid data centers keep increasing. Traditional manual-dependent equipment room inspections have revealed significant shortcomings in efficiency, objectivity, and real-time responsiveness, struggling to meet higher demands for operational stability and reliability. Addressing this challenge, this paper proposes and implements a graphics-based simulation and joint debugging system for power grid data center information rooms. This system aims to provide a reproducible, scalable virtual inspection verification platform. Utilizing Unity as the execution engine, it constructs realistic 3D room environments and equipment models. Built-in NavMesh/Agent technology handles path optimization and obstacle avoidance, while a UI panel enables visual display of equipment status and historical path playback. Python serves as the control terminal for task scheduling and data processing. Both components establish bidirectional communication via TCP Socket, forming a closed-loop process: "command issuance → navigation execution → status collection → result display → data export." Communication and execution performance were evaluated in a loopback network environment: end-to-end transmission latency remained stable below 20 ms (minimum 0.69 ms), while internal response time from command issuance to execution in Unity was controlled within 1 s. Results demonstrate the system’s engineering characteristics of low cost, scalability, and robust real-time performance, providing effective support for intelligent server room inspection research and implementation.
